description.plain:
Beatrice Ilejay Laus (born June 3, 2000 in Iloilo City, Philippines), formerly known as Bea and best known as beabadoobee, is a British-Filipino singer-songwriter based in London, England.

Bea’s music is influenced by artists Alex G, Karen O, and Florist.

Bea released her debut EP Lice on March 1, 2018. In July 2018, Bea would. later sign to label Dirty Hit, an independent record label based in London, England. Her second EP, Patched Up was released on December 7, 2018. On April 25, 2019, she released her third EP – Loveworm. On October 14, 2019, she released her fourth EP titled Space Cadet.

In 2020, Bea’s 2017 song “Coffee” was sampled in rapper Powfu’s viral Tik Tok hit death bed (coffee for your head), which became a global hit thanks to video app TikTok.

With this newfound attention, Bea’s debut studio album Fake It Flowers was soon to follow, with singles like “Care,” “Sorry,” “Worth It,” and “How Was Your Day?” preceding the release.

In 2021, Bea released her fifth EP, titled Our Extended Play, which she co-produced with The 1975 frontman Matty Healy.

Her most recent album is Beatopia which was released in 2022. Following the release of the album, “the perfect pair” started to gain traction on TikTok and other short-form video platforms, and the audio continued to be used well into 2023.

songs.title: Glue Song

description.plain:
“Glue Song” is a love song about finding someone special and becoming attached to them. beabadoobee sings about experiencing this unexpected connection with someone that is unlike anything she has ever felt before, using glue as a metaphor to symbolize the bond she feels to her new partner.

On October 28, 2022, prior to its release, bea performed this song live for the first time during her concert at the Brooklyn Steel in Brooklyn, New York while on her Beatopia Tour. She then posted an Instagram Reel of her live performance the following day on October 29th, 2022.

The song’s cover art seems to be inspired by the album cover of Kokyuu by Lily Chou-Chou, as when placed next to each other, there are clear similarities between the two.

songs.title: Coffee

description.plain:
“Coffee” is a light acoustic ballad written by and performed by beabadoobee. In it, Bea lightly touches on the themes of mental health, relationships, and how they play together. In a Vice profile piece, Bea mentions that this song was about her boyfriend, Søren:

It was about my boyfriend, Søren, because he has green eyes. It was about him—it’s the cringiest love song about me making coffee for him.

In an interview with Pigeons with Planes, Bea confirms that this is the first song that she’s written for the guitar.

In the same interview, she also says

I’ve realized I can’t play to a click. ‘Coffee’ is all over the place. The tempo is so wack.

Notably, “Coffee” was sampled on Powfu’s death bed (coffee for your head) in 2019, which was re-released in 2020.

songs.title: ‎the way things go

description.plain:
On the 20th of July 2023, Beabadoobee’s first single off her third album, ‘the way things go’ was released. This upbeat breakup song reminisces on the subtle issues experienced in and after her relationship with her former boyfriend of 7 years, Soren Harrison.

She debuted ‘the way things go’ during the Beatopia Tour in Berlin, Germany, when she mentioned the pressure she experienced to release the song. She also went mentioned that:

It’s one of my favourite songs I’ve written so far

Beabadoobee states that this will be her only breakup song of the album as she focuses more on writing love songs. This stems from her relationship with Jacob Erland who inspired ‘Glue Song’.

songs.title: Tired

description.plain:
“Tired” is about the stressed and scattered brain of every human out there. It’s about that era, that period, that moment in time we all go through where everything seems pointless and you feel like you’re drowning in an endless pit.

Throughout the song, Bea uses “I” or “you” referring to herself, which shows how distanced they feel from herself. This clever addition also makes it feel to the listener that she is talking to them, to relate to others who feel the same.

songs.title: Ripples

description.plain:
“Ripples” is a folk-inspired song about finding yourself again after being away from people you love. After the success of Fake It Flowers, Bea went on tour alone, away from her friends and former boyfriend Soren. During this time of isolation, Bea took time time to reflect on herself and her relationships and had some songwriting help from lead singer Matthew Healy of The 1975.

The verses show Bea’s struggle to be emotionally open with her friends after being alone for so long. In the chorus, Bea hints at the codependency she refrains from, a struggle she alludes to later in the album with “Don’t Get the Deal.” The title is an illusion to water ripples and her reflection in the water; these are metaphors of the façade she puts up while around others.

songs.title: Pictures of Us

description.plain:
The 1975’s Matty Healy served as a mentor for Bea during the creation of Beatopia, a benefit of her contract with Dirty Hit. Pictures of Us is a reworking of a song written for Healy’s ever-in-limbo solo project “Drive Like I Do,” a reference to one of the band’s many early names.

Healy had the song and three others pretty much ready for release, before being sidetracked working on the band’s fifth studio album: Being Funny In A Foreign Language. Because of this Healy offered up one of the songs to Bea. Referencing this in an interview with NME he said:

“I have to sit on stuff and then edit it before I love it, by the time I sat on it and started editing it I was making a 75 record and Bea had fallen in love with Pictures Of Us.”

Bea took the song and made changes to the pre-chorus, changing the lyrics about Healy’s childhood to those of her own. This portion is written about a girl Bea used to know, and all the crazy things they did together as teenagers. Bea had previously written about this girl on the record “Fake It Flowers”.

songs.title: Talk

description.plain:
“Talk” is an energetic guitar-driven track where beabadoobee describes her regular days where she’d often go out on a Tuesday night when she should remain at home to relax for her midweek duties for the following morning.

On March 23, 2022, she spoke with NME in an interview, where she’s depicted herself opting to enjoy life:

I wrote ‘Talk’ just after my first album. I was obsessed with Tuesday because I thought it was the best night to go out, not too much chaos but just enough to have a good time. Generally, it’s about doing things that aren’t necessarily healthy or great for you but you can’t help indulging. It’s like that unavoidable feeling that you get, you can’t get rid of it and you know it’s bad but you love it really and it’s whatever, so you do it anyway.

On March 15, 2022, Bea first teased the instrumental on her Twitter, telling her followers to subscribe to her mailing list to stay up to date on her latest releases:

description.plain:
With a bedroom pop and indie rock sound and insanely catchy production, “10:36” serves as a perfect summer track to live out all of your early 2000s coming-of-age movie dreams.

“10:36” captures the intense and specific feelings that come with loneliness and love; dropping back to a soft vocal line over a single guitar, beabadobee repeats, “I know you thought it was just us / I didn’t think you’d fall in love / You’re just a warm body to hold / At night when I’m feeling all alone,” sharing that while she gets comfort from being with this person at night, there’s nothing deeper in this relationship for her.

Although harsh to hear, beabadoobee stunningly encapsulates these specific and crushing feelings from both her perspective and the experience of an unrequited lover.

“10:36” is a thrilling taste of Beatopia, which is set to bring listeners into the world and imagination of seven-year-old beabadoobee through a distinctive mix of bedroom pop, fuzzy rock, and psychedelia.

songs.title: Last Day On Earth

description.plain:
“Last Day On Earth” is Beabadoobee’s first single since the release of her debut album Fake It Flowers. Bea wrote this song with Matty Healy from The 1975. Matty also produced the track, alongside drummer George Daniel.
In an interview for Rolling Stone, Bea said:


“’Last Day on Earth’ is about all the things I would have done had I known we were going into a lockdown and the world was going to change the way it has. It was written shortly after the first main lockdown and lyrically it’s me reflecting on how it would feel if we all knew ahead of time what was going to happen. All the things I would have done if I knew it was the last day of our old normality.

I wrote and recorded the EP on a farm with Matty and George from the 1975 in the countryside. It was really nice being able to create together, my first time writing and recording in that kind of setting. I wanted to experiment on the sounds and sonics even more and the EP to me has a feeling of togetherness to it… How we’re all in this joined as one".

“This one’s not about me, and I really don’t want anyone to think it’s about Soren! A friend told me this story, about what was essentially an abusive relationship. And it made me really angry, because this is just something that happens so often these days. At times, I feel like I’ve fallen into that trap, where I feel like I’m only doing things to impress my boyfriend. But every time I sing this song it reminds me that I am my own person, and I can do whatever the fuck I want.“ – Bea for i-D

In Bea’s Spotify Magazine, she claims “This song is about horrible men in your life that you may experience – if you’re lucky hopefully you never will. Its about the frustration you feel when you can’t be yourself.”

songs.title: You Lie All the Time

description.plain:
‘You Lie All the Time’ tells of a relationship shrouded in a fog of doubt, where Bea and her lover mutually tiptoe around serious problems in their relationship.

Tired of confrontation and afraid of loss yet being painfully aware of it all, the two practice turning a blind eye (in lying that everything is fine). They play hot potato on the definitive closure of these problems, perpetually leaving loose ends.

songs.title: Horen Sarrison

description.plain:
“Horen Sarrison” is the ninth track on Beabadoobee’s debut album Fake It Flowers and is named after her boyfriend, director Soren Harrison. She flipped his initials in its title (Flipping the two initial letters is called a Spoonerism).

On Apple Music, Bea said: “I thought it was kind of funny to switch the two letters and call it ‘Horen Sarrison’. It’s just so stupid.”

In the song’s Spotify Storyline, she claims: “This is a love song and about how you can lose yourself in a relationship. I wanted a song on the album that reminded me of like a Disney soundtrack.”

songs.title: Animal Noises

description.plain:
“Animal Noises” is the third track off Beabadoobee’s EP Our Extended Play. It reflects on the fear of growing up and emotes a feeling of nostalgia for the simple and wholesome moments of childhood.

This song was produced by Matthew Healy and George Daniel from The 1975. In fact, the country feel in “Animal Noises” is quite reminiscent of the band’s “The Birthday Party” from their album Notes On A Conditional Form, which also explored this genre.
